^b@2djneill:  OK these 10 example hands have been wild and wooly, 
precision makes auctions very fun sometimes.
But the key principles remain:
Bid your PRIMARY suits first
And, if South (1@d responder) could have 0 HCP, we pretend THEY OPENED and bid accordingly.

Isabelle10:  in general does the 1 club opener always try to bid again after interference
djneill:  North could Pass, often with 17-19 BAL and no stopper
Or, if West had bid 2@s, not 1@s, that might silence many North hands for a bit.
But North should strain to bid, the 1@c told nothing about the shape of the hand, it is time to show it.

I will mention that interference against a strong club is the best defense to a strong club
It is important not to sit on your hands when the opponents open 1@c
If you do not overcall, they will tend to find the best contract.

djneill:  Good question came up, isn't North's first Pass over 1@s always a TRAP pass, with long spades?
North could have something like   @s Jxx  @h AKx  @d KQJx  @c KJx
In that case, North would have no bid
So North would just Pass over 1@s
Perhaps North could double, but it's close
southuist:  Because I was wondering how south tells the difference, and how do you alert a trap pass?
Do you alert it?
djneill:  No Pass is alertable in bridge, it's always either "nothing to say" or "trap"
Ok I guess there may be a Pass sometimes but it is rare, that it is alertable.|
